    <p class="text-xl mb-4">10-15 MINUTES &bull; 2-3 TIMES A DAY</p>

    <p class="mb-4">Outside turns are definitely easiest to learn first, so practice that until your dog is starting to watch your leg and turn when you turn. When they're reliably turning with you then start working on inside turns.</p>

    <h3 class="text-lg font-bold mt-6 mb-3">What about dog walks in the mean time?</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">It's likely that you'll still be walking your dog on a leash while they learn how to walk loosely on a leash. That's where a harness comes back in. Hook them up to their harness and let them put pressure if they want. Remember, the feeling of the harness is totally different than the feeling of the collar. Because of that, your dog can understand that the rules are different for each.</p>

    <p class="mb-4">For 95% of the walk, you'll walk your dog on their harness. Then, for the last 5% of the walk, you'll switch to their collar and practice loose leash walking. Don't worry about covering too much ground in that final 5% of the walk because you might be doing a <em>lot</em> of pop-and-turns! You might even want to finish the walk, clip to the leash, and do your loose leash walking in the driveway or the parking lot.</p>

    <p>Slowly, you'll bump that 5% to 10%. Then 20% of the walk. Then half of the walk. Before you know it you'll be throwing that harness away.</p>
